<h2><a name="comments"></a>Responses</h2>
<dl>	<dd><a name="comment_2204" ></a>
	<p><em><strong>Paul</strong> replies:</em> I thought this was a site about why we're NOT voting. Spoiling a ballot IS voting. They are counted as part of the turn-out. If 100 people are entitled to vote and 50 do so, the turn-out is 50%. If 10 of the 50 spoil their ballot, the turn-out is still announced as 50%. What's the point in spoiling your ballot paper if it looks like you've participated in the election?</p>
	<small>
	written 28th Apr 2005 <!-- | <a
    href="/abuse/?postid=1522&amp;commentid=2204">abusive?</a>
    --> </small>
	</dd>
	<dd><a name="comment_2209" ></a>
	<p><em><strong>Red Deathy</strong> replies:</em> Many people I've argued with consider it to be not voting, although I argue the case you've just put.</p> <p>So far, though, as I can see, this is a site about not voting for any candidate standing, and I see spoiling as recording a none vote while reserving my right and capacity to vote in future should I so choose.</p> <p>I'll also add that candidates and agents inspect all spoiult papers on the off chance they can claim a distinguishing mark...</p>
	<small>
	written 28th Apr 2005 <!-- | <a
    href="/abuse/?postid=1522&amp;commentid=2209">abusive?</a>
    --> </small>
	</dd>
</dl>
